eti! mbona mimi mume wangu alikuwa kijana wa kwa fulani?

the fact that <desi> is <desir> here can probably be ascribed to a phonological rule, where the occurrence of [d] (as well as [q]) as part of the word percludes the pronunciation of [r]. Does this apply to the LF morphs [t] or [k] as well? <desír do> is fine, though.
mtu ni nani hapa mtu wangu ni nani?
my person is who here? who is my person?
hee a ma barakí aní heeʔéʔ a ma?
bring him here! bring him here!
<ku> here must be a short form for <kuungá'> as well as <kuúng>, as the following verb indicates that the speaker is clearly referring to a 2nd person plural entity
I will bring him then you catch him
aníng u huw daqane ku otaak

nguna báy gitláy qwaláng baroʕo awaan

aso dír deti, detití iʔa qasee

so when he (i.e. the sorcerer) arrived
pale kwenye mkuyu, misukule wapo hapa wanatazama.

I have interpreted phrases such as <i ya/and> as 'it is possible'. Here, <ya/and> (in a transitive (?) sense), seems to mean 'agree'.

The choice of personal pronoun is interesting here, given that it is feminine ('you woman'), whereas the assumed addressee (researcher A.H.) is male. This could simply be a speaking error. Note also that <tlakweema> is N.
in this case <aama> 'grandmother', and <aako> 'grandfather' are being used to mean 'woman' and 'man' (perhaps with a slight sense of notoriety)

mchoyo hataki hata kusikia nyayo za miguu ya mtu
a greedy person doesn't like the footprints of a person
note that <muukú do> is operating here as a single entity (in its role as a greeting). It is encoded in the selector as N
siku moja akamwambia mume wake, mume wangu!
note the conjugation of <báw> (which is 1st person), here (supposedly F.Pst), the form is <bét>, which does not fit into any of your established verbal paradigms.

here (as opposed to the exact same phrase above), the <i> has been analyzed as part of the verb

does the occurrence of the Background Aspect (?) trigger Subjunctive in the following VP? The <ngi> selector and the (probable) level PA on the verb <tles> are hints here. The two VP seem very linked here (i.e. 'when she arrived (such that) he helped her lift up'). Note that <tleés> is not exactly 'lift up', but rather 'lift a load onto the back or head'
she went, when she arrived, he lifted up her load onto her back
ina hiʔít iwa hardát ngina tles

the reason the subjunctive is not triggered following the background aspect here is because the two phrases seem to not be in the same larger utterance, but two different utterances (i.e. there seems to be a pause in between the two)
she looked him up and down! she coveted him, she wanted to eat him
nguna gaʕaʕeér gaʕaʕeér ngwa ilatleerés ngwa ʕaymár wa sláʔ
